		 Application Form for Grass-Root Basic Research Fund

   Project title: Fast Multidimensional FFT__________  Date: May 25, 1995______

   Name:_Alan Karp_____________ Telnet: 857-6766___  Location Code:  ___________

   Supervisor: Rajiv Gupta_________________________ Telnet: 857-8507____________


   Did you inform your immediate manager of your intention to work on this 
   research topic? (It is ok if you didn't.)

   (  ) Yes   ( x ) No.

   Type of the project: mark the most appropriate ones

   (   ) Physical science (   ) Computer Science   (    ) System 

   ( ) medical         ( ) software             (x) signal processing 
   ( ) material         ( ) hardware             ( ) measurement system
   ( ) device         ( ) circuit              ( ) manufacturing system
   ( ) physics

   (   ) Other, please state: ________________________


   How long the project will take?

     Should be doable in a summer since the basic coding is done.
     Might even have time to parallelize on our cluster.

   If successful, which business should the investigation impact? (N.A., if not
   applicable)

     Improvements to HP's non-existent scientific subroutine library.

   Do you need to purchase any additional equipment or accessories for this 
   project? If yes, how much money is needed?

     Student should have a workstation with the largest possible
     memory.  If one is available for off-hours use, no new equipment
     will be needed.

   Note: Every research project should conclude with a seminar opened to the
	 general public.

     I'd be delighted.

   I've never seen a grant proposal that didn't ask for some details,
   so here it is.

     Multidimensional FFTs are done by taking one dimensional FFTs
     along each coordinate direction.  This process involves either long
     stride access along all but one of the dimensions or a transpose of
     the data.  I have developed a method that avoids an explicit
     transpose step yet still works at low stride.  Work done over 3
     years ago before I joined HP showed the method to be effective on
     Cray and IBM vector machines.  I'd like to do the same for
     workstations and, time permitting, in parallel on a cluster.


