	Dear Dr Karp,

	When I looked at SIAM a few days ago, I saw an article of yours about 
	bit reversal in FFT's. (I liked very much your approach to discuss these 
	things in close connection with modern computer architectures)
	This article suggest that you have some interest in FFT's in general.
	As I have mentioned in our entry to the GB competition I have devolopped
	3-dim FFT packages. I have an all purpose (not processor optimized) FFT
	that gives very good performance on a wide range of computer architectures
	ranging from RISC microprocessors to vector supercomputers. The tuning 
	for all these architectures is done by setting one single parameter, 
	namely the cache size (on vector machines it is set to 0). This routine 
	can be up to 25 percent slower than vendor optimized routines 
	but in some cases it is actually faster. My routines 
	are significanly faster than the software that can be found in various 
	public domain libraries. In addition 
	to this all purpose version I still have 2 versions that are optimized 
	for the IBM power2 and the MIPS R8000 architecture. My routines are 
	used by several research groups in the field of electronic structure in the US 
	and Europe and I also gave a nonexclusive license agreement to a commercial company.
	
	FFTs are used in many fields of science and engineering and I am wondering 
	whether it might be useful to make these routines available to a 
	wider public outside the field of electronic structure where people 
	know about my FFT's. It seems to me that there is a certain gap in good 
	standarized public software. With the BLAS and LAPACK standard there 
	is now efficient public domain software available for these fields,
	but for the field of FFT's nothing of comparable quality is available 
	according to my knowledge.

	My first question to you is whether you think that introducing a
	standard software for both one and higher dimensionsl FFTs in the 
	same way as it was done for basic and linear algebra problems would 
	really be useful to a wide community of users and feasible.

	If this was the case I think a highly respected person in the field 
	of scientific computing would be needed to coordinate the efforts. 
	(Since this is a major project it will certainly involve several people,
	I could for instance contribute higher dimensional FFT's) 
	Would you be interested (and have time) to coordinate such a project?
	

Best regards

	Stefan  


